content:
TITLE: Knex From Table (JS)
DESCRIPTION: Illustrates how to specify the table to select from in a Knex.js query using the `from` method. Shows a basic example.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_7

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex.select('*')
  .from('users')
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Knex.js WHERE Clause with Key-Value Syntax
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates the key-value syntax for the `where` clause in Knex.js, specifying the column and value to match.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_100

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex('users').where('id', 1)
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Knex.js WHERE RAW Clause
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates the `whereRaw` clause, which allows specifying a raw SQL expression within the WHERE clause. Bindings can be used to safely inject values into the query.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_125

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex('users').whereRaw('id = ?', [1])
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Knex.js WHERE Clause with Grouped Chain
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to group `where` clauses using a function to define logical groupings, combined with `orWhere` for alternative conditions.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_102

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex('users').where(function() {
  this.where('id', 1).orWhere('id', '>', 10)
}).orWhere({name: 'Tester'})
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Knex Transaction with Async/Await and Transacting (TypeScript)
DESCRIPTION: This example showcases using `knex.transaction` with `async/await` and the `transacting` method, providing an alternative way to manage transactions with asynchronous operations.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/transactions.md#_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
try {
  await knex.transaction(async trx => {

    const books = [
      {title: 'Canterbury Tales'},
      {title: 'Moby Dick'},
      {title: 'Hamlet'}
    ];

    const ids = await knex('catalogues')
      .insert({
        name: 'Old Books'
      }, 'id')
      .transacting(trx)

    books.forEach(book => book.catalogue_id = ids[0])
    await knex('books')
      .insert(books)
      .transacting(trx)

    console.log(inserts.length + ' new books saved.')
  })
} catch (error) {
  console.error(error);
}
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Running Latest Migrations with Knex.js
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates how to run all pending migrations and then execute seed files using Knex.js. It shows the asynchronous nature of migration execution and how to chain promises to ensure proper execution order.  It uses the `knex.migrate.latest()` and `knex.seed.run()` functions, handling promises to execute migrations and seeds sequentially.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/migrations.md#_snippet_22

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex.migrate.latest()
  .then(function() {
    return knex.seed.run();
  })
  .then(function() {
    // migrations are finished
  });
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Knex.js WHERE Clause with Functions (Subqueries)
DESCRIPTION: This snippet shows the use of functions within the `where` clause to create subqueries. It allows for complex conditional logic using nested `where` and `whereIn` clauses.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_101

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex('users')
  .where((builder) =>
    builder
      .whereIn('id', [1, 11, 15])
      .whereNotIn('id', [17, 19])
  )
  .andWhere(function() {
    this.where('id', '>', 10)
  })
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Knex Transaction with Query Builder (JavaScript)
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates using `knex.transaction` with a callback function where the transaction object (`trx`) is used as a query builder. It inserts a catalogue and then books associated with that catalogue. The transaction commits if all operations succeed, and rolls back if any operation fails.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/transactions.md#_snippet_0

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex.transaction(function(trx) {

  const books = [
    {title: 'Canterbury Tales'},
    {title: 'Moby Dick'},
    {title: 'Hamlet'}
  ];

  return trx
    .insert({name: 'Old Books'}, 'id')
    .into('catalogues')
    .then(function(ids) {
      books.forEach((book) => book.catalogue_id = ids[0]);
      return trx('books').insert(books);
    });
})
.then(function(inserts) {
  console.log(inserts.length + ' new books saved.');
})
.catch(function(error) {
  // If we get here, that means that 
  // neither the 'Old Books' catalogues insert,
  // nor any of the books inserts will have taken place.
  console.error(error);
});
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Insert Query with Knex.js
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to create an insert query in Knex.js. It takes either a hash of properties to be inserted into the row, or an array of inserts, to be executed as a single insert command. It covers single inserts, multi-row inserts, and the use of the `returning` option.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_44

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
// Returns [1] in "mysql", "sqlite", "oracle"; 
// [] in "postgresql" 
// unless the 'returning' parameter is set.
knex('books').insert({title: 'Slaughterhouse Five'})

// Normalizes for empty keys on multi-row insert:
knex('coords').insert([{x: 20}, {y: 30},  {x: 10, y: 20}])

// Returns [2] in "mysql", "sqlite"; [2, 3] in "postgresql"
knex
  .insert(
    [
      { title: 'Great Gatsby' }, 
      { title: 'Fahrenheit 451' }
    ],
    ['id']
  )
  .into('books')
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: On Conflict Merge with Knex.js
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to use the `onConflict` and `merge` methods to perform an UPSERT operation, updating the existing row with new data if a conflict occurs. This example merges all columns.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_50

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex('tableName')
  .insert({
    email: "ignore@example.com",
    name: "John Doe"
  })
  .onConflict('email')
  .merge()
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Using Explicit Transaction Management with Async Code (TS)
DESCRIPTION: This example illustrates how to use explicit transaction management in Knex with asynchronous code using TypeScript. It uses the `knex.transaction` method to start a transaction and defines an async function that can perform operations within the transaction. It demonstrates both rolling back within the async function and handling errors in the transaction to ensure proper rollback.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/faq/recipes.md#_snippet_6

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
await knex.transaction(trx => {
  async function stuff() {
    trx.rollback(new Error('Foo'));
  };
  stuff()
    .then(() => {
      // do something
    });
});
```

LANGUAGE: typescript
CODE:
```
try {
  await knex.transaction(trx => {
    async function stuff() {
      trx.rollback(new Error('always explicit rollback this time'));
    }
    stuff();
  }); 
  // transaction was committed
  } catch (err) {
    // transaction was rolled back 
  }
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Knex.js WHERE NULL Clause
DESCRIPTION: This snippet demonstrates the `whereNull` clause, which selects records where the specified column's value is NULL.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_117

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex('users').whereNull('updated_at')
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: On Conflict Merge with Separate Updates in Knex.js
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates updating data differently from the insert data during an UPSERT operation. The example updates the 'name' column to "John Doe The Second" if a conflict occurs on the 'email' column.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_53

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
const timestamp = Date.now();
knex('tableName')
  .insert({
    email: "ignore@example.com",
    name: "John Doe",
    created_at: timestamp,
    updated_at: timestamp,
  })
  .onConflict('email')
  .merge({
    name: "John Doe The Second",
  })
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Knex.js WHERE NOT IN Clause
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates the `whereNotIn` clause, which excludes records where the column's value is present in the provided array.
SOURCE: https://github.com/knex/documentation/blob/main/src/guide/query-builder.md#_snippet_116

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex('users').whereNotIn('id', [1, 2, 3])
```

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
knex('users')
  .where('name', 'like', '%Test%')
  .orWhereNotIn('id', [1, 2, 3])
```

